solely devoted to women poets.

00:39:32.700 --> 00:39:36.100
I mean, they're a small proportion.

00:39:36.100 --> 00:39:39.500
But even in the Qajar times,
there's a tazkirah that's related

00:39:39.500 --> 00:39:42.890
to women poets and specifically
those of the shah's harem.

00:39:42.890 --> 00:39:46.290
So they usually tend to
focus on royal families.

00:39:46.290 --> 00:39:49.690 position:56%
It's much harder to find kind of
on-the-street women poets going back

00:39:49.690 --> 00:39:53.080
to early and modern times.

00:39:53.080 --> 00:39:56.480
But certainly we do
find tazkirahs of royal,

00:39:56.480 --> 00:39:59.880
elite women who are
composing poetry.

00:39:59.880 --> 00:40:03.280
&gt;&gt; So essentially just [inaudible]
it is that more and more --

00:40:03.280 --> 00:40:06.670
it was sort of a regional
development in Persia

00:40:06.670 --> 00:40:10.070
and [inaudible] later
trends that [inaudible].

00:40:10.070 --> 00:40:13.470
It was just phenomena
of [inaudible].

00:40:13.470 --> 00:40:16.860
There were a lot of the
[inaudible] regions and centers.

00:40:16.860 --> 00:40:20.260
Is that a --

00:40:20.260 --> 00:40:23.660
&gt;&gt; Kevin Schwartz: Yeah.

00:40:23.660 --> 00:40:27.050
I mean, again, I think it's a good
way to explain tazkirah production

00:40:27.050 --> 00:40:30.450
at this time, that there seems
to be less transregional overlap

00:40:30.450 --> 00:40:33.850
but certainly not for Persian
language and literature in general.

00:40:33.850 --> 00:40:37.250
I mean, a lot of the great
newspapers in Persian were cropping

00:40:37.250 --> 00:40:40.640
up in Bombay, they were cropping
up elsewhere, in Istanbul.

00:40:40.640 --> 00:40:44.040
And they were crucial in the
constitutional revolution.

00:40:44.040 --> 00:40:47.440 position:56%
And of course you have transregional
connections among the Parsi

00:40:47.440 --> 00:40:50.830
community and their impact in both
philology and education in Iran.

00:40:50.830 --> 00:40:54.230
So I mean, that's the one
thing I have to square.

00:40:54.230 --> 00:40:57.630 position:56%
And, you know, again, it's a
consequence of trying to use mapping

00:40:57.630 --> 00:41:01.020
and keep it restrictive so I
can actually map, you know,

00:41:01.020 --> 00:41:04.420
a select group of texts and
not have to map of entirety

00:41:04.420 --> 00:41:07.820
of Persian literary
sphere but also be kind

00:41:07.820 --> 00:41:11.220
of more attuned to those trends.

00:41:11.220 --> 00:41:14.610
Because I mean, transregionalism
was still happening.

00:41:14.610 --> 00:41:18.010
It just wasn't happening
in the way, you know --

00:41:18.010 --> 00:41:19.520
[ Inaudible ]

00:41:19.520 --> 00:41:21.730
Right, right.

00:41:21.730 --> 00:41:23.930
I mean, it's going to
have to be situated

00:41:23.930 --> 00:41:26.140
in the larger kind of
transregional moment.

00:41:26.140 --> 00:41:28.350
But I think that's, you
know, definitely, again,

00:41:28.350 --> 00:41:30.550
one drawback of this work that
doesn't bring in different texts.

00:41:30.550 --> 00:41:32.760
And so that was my
caveat at the beginning.

00:41:32.760 --> 00:41:34.970
This is a whole kind
of multilingual sphere.

00:41:34.970 --> 00:41:37.170
There's a whole other, you know,

00:41:37.170 --> 00:41:39.380
genre going on with [foreign
language] that also are kind

00:41:39.380 --> 00:41:41.590
of integrated into the space.

00:41:41.590 --> 00:41:43.800
But for purposes of practicality,
unless this is crowd-sourced,

00:41:43.800 --> 00:41:46.510
I just had to focus on tazkirahs.

00:41:46.510 --> 00:41:56.510
[ Inaudible ]

00:41:56.510 --> 00:42:00.010
No, it's just -- it's
an ongoing project.

00:42:00.010 --> 00:42:03.510
And the idea is that more
people contribute to this

00:42:03.510 --> 00:42:07.010
and start creating entries
for Urdu tazkirahs as well.

00:42:07.010 --> 00:42:10.510
And you begin to see a big trend
in mid-19th century South Asia

00:42:10.510 --> 00:42:14.010
where most of the tazkirahs

00:42:14.010 --> 00:42:17.510
of Persian poets are actually
being produced now in Urdu.

00:42:17.510 --> 00:42:21.010
So they're written in Urdu, but
then you have the actual selections

00:42:21.010 --> 00:42:24.510
that are in Persian because
it's about Persian poets.

00:42:24.510 --> 00:42:28.010
So I'm hoping people will get
involved on that side of it.

00:42:28.010 --> 00:42:31.510
I think there are tazkirahs
for Ottoman Turkish.

00:42:31.510 --> 00:42:35.010
But, again, it's kind of a vast
project, but I really wanted

00:42:35.010 --> 00:42:38.510
